Narrative 4, a global non-profit organisation, which seeks to build empathy among young people and bridge ideological divides, will hold its first story exchange in Nigeria on the Nigerian Civil War of 1967 to 1970. The event, which is slated for the evening of Tuesday, January 14, 2019 at the Exhibition Pavilion, Area 10, Garki in Abuja, will also feature music, spoken word poetry and a keynote address on ‘Empathy’ as the basis for national unity. According to a press statement sent out by the group, it said “No anecdote about Nigeria is complete without a reference to the sentiments and divides that plague this uniquely diverse country of over 190m people.” “Nigeria is home to generations for whom ethnic identities function as an ‘otherness’. Perhaps the most visible of these divisions is what is referred to as a mutual disdain and distrust between major parts of the South Eastern and Northern Nigeria. Causation for this is well known – the Civil War of 1967-1970,” it said. Narrative 4 noted, however, that the the sentiments therefore, become fodder for populists, hate merchants and politicians to exploit, fan and leverage upon to cause crises, divisions and, many times, outright bile and hatred. It added that many of the conversations on the civil war have been “devoid of empathy as they oscillate around claims of total victimhood, villainy and sainthood.” The group pointed out that it harnesses the power of the story exchange to equip and embolden young adults to improve their lives, their communities, and the world at large. The event, which is tagged ‘Introducing Handshake across the Niger Story Exchange’ with a theme of ‘post-war’ unity, it consists of an exchange of personal stories and experiences both during the civil war. “The stories will be exchanged across Gender, inter-generational and inter-regional/sides. The aim is to ensure that the key missing ingredient is found – Empathy,” it further highlighted.